values:
I downloaded a bunch of "Filk" some time ago.  Filk is folk music with Science Fiction themes.  I got this song from the website of the record company that published it. I didn't listen to it for a few days, and when I finally did, I just smiled. Then I listened to it again.  I can't find the publisher now but I googled the title and found the song.

http://infogroep.be/files/The_Eternal_Flame_God_Wrote_in_Lisp.mp3


Is this Parody or someone who it seroius?  I can't tell.  I think it's a good song anyway.  It was one of the many things that inspired the post I'm going to do next. (Still writing it)


Found it here http://igwe.vub.ac.be/GodWroteInLisp

the Song is by Julia Ecklar

I was taught assembler 
in my second year of school. 
It's kinda like construction work -- 
with a toothpick for a tool. 
So when I made my senior year, 
I threw my code away, 
And learned the way to program 
that I still prefer today.

Now, some folks on the Internet 
put their faith in C++. 
They swear that it's so powerful, 
it's what God used for us. 
And maybe it lets mortals dredge 
their objects from the C. 
But I think that explains 
why only God can make a tree.

For God wrote in Lisp code 
When he filled the leaves with green. 
The fractal flowers and recursive roots: 
The most lovely hack I've seen. 
And when I ponder snowflakes, 
never finding two the same, 
I know God likes a language 
with its own four-letter name.

Now, I've used a SUN under Unix, 
so I've seen what C can hold. 
I've surfed for Perls, found what Fortran's for, 
Got that Java stuff down cold. 
Though the chance that I'd write COBOL code 
is a SNOBOL's chance in Hell. 
And I basically hate hieroglyphs, 
so I won't use APL.

Now, God must know all these languages, 
and a few I haven't named. 
But the Lord made sure, when each sparrow falls, 
that its flesh will be reclaimed. 
And the Lord could not count grains of sand 
with a 32-bit word. 
Who knows where we would go to 
if Lisp weren't what he preferred?

And God wrote in Lisp code 
Every creature great and small. 
Don't search the disk drive for man.c, 
When the listing's on the wall. 
And when I watch the lightning burn 
Unbelievers to a crisp, 
I know God had six days to work, 
So he wrote it all in Lisp.

Yes, God had a deadline. 
So he wrote it all in Lisp.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

For years I've been listening tech shows talk about blogging.  I never thought much about blogging myself.  In the future I'd love to do a PODcast but this seems cheeper and easier. Also I can do this in odd places, with background noise, and quiet places where talking into a microphone would be inappropriate.  Right now I just have the free account, but if I find I acually use the journal I'll pay the $25, which seems like a deal.  

I don't like how I can't access my email from work, but it seems that I can get to my Live Journal. When I was in School, mostly High School but also College, I had to keep a journal.  I didn't always keep up with that either, but after college I decided that I would still keep a journal.  With no one reading my Journal I just wasn't inspired to write.

Will anyone read this?  I doubt it, but who knows?  At least someone could read it which may be enough to make me write.
